## C. 1-st round of optimization

The optimization problem of $e[u]$ is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\min _{e[u]} & \left.e[u]-\hat{e}[u]+\kappa \lambda_{\hat{e}_{u}}\right|^{2}+\left|e[u]-\hat{e}[u]+\kappa \lambda_{\hat{e}_{u}}\right|^{2}+ \\
& \left.\left.\mid e[u]-\hat{e}[u]+\kappa \lambda_{\hat{e}_{u}}\right|^{2}\right. \\
\text { s.t. } & (1-e[u]) e[u]=0,0 \leq e[u] \leq 1
\end{aligned}
$$

By introducing the Lagrange multiplier $\lambda_{1, u}$ to constraint (15b), the optimal $e[u]$ can be expressed as

$$
e[u]= \begin{cases}\frac{\lambda_{1, u} / 2+\hat{e}[u]+\hat{e}[u]+\hat{e}\left[u]-\kappa\left(\lambda_{\hat{e}[u]}+\lambda_{\hat{e}[u]}+\lambda_{\hat{e}[u]}\right)}{2+\lambda_{1, u}} & 0 \leq e[u] \leq 1 \\ 1 & e[u]>1 \\ 0 & e[u]<0\end{cases}
$$

and $\lambda_{1, u}$ is expressed as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \lambda_{1, u}=\max \left\{0,-2\left(3+\hat{e}[u]+\hat{e}[u]+\hat{e}[u]-\kappa\left(\lambda_{\hat{e}[u]}+\lambda_{\hat{e}[u]}+\right.\right.\right. \\
& \left.\left.\lambda_{\hat{e}[u]}\right)\right), 2\left(\hat{e}[u]+\hat{e}[u]+\hat{e}[u]-\kappa\left(\lambda_{\hat{e}[u]}+\lambda_{\hat{e}[u]}+\lambda_{\hat{e}[u]}\right)\right)\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

Similarly, using the Lagrange multipliers method, the optimal $\alpha_{u}, c, \bar{\alpha}_{u}, \bar{\eta}$ and $\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{u, n_{1}}$ can be expressed as

$$
\alpha_{u}=\left(2 \bar{\alpha}_{u}+2 \kappa \lambda_{\bar{\alpha}_{u}}-\lambda_{2, u}\right) / 2, c=\lambda_{3} \sigma_{u}^{2} / 2+\bar{c}-\kappa \lambda_{\bar{c}}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \bar{\alpha}_{u}=\lambda_{4, u} / 2+\bar{\alpha}_{u} \bar{c}-\kappa \lambda_{\bar{\alpha}_{u}}, \gamma_{u}=\left(\bar{\gamma}_{u}+\boldsymbol{q}^{H} \boldsymbol{b}_{u} \beta_{u}-\kappa\left(\lambda_{\bar{\gamma}_{u}}\right.\right. \\
& \left.\left.+\lambda_{\gamma_{u}}\right)\right) / 4, \bar{\eta}=\frac{\bar{\eta}+\kappa \lambda_{\bar{\eta}}+\eta\left(\bar{\eta}-\kappa \lambda_{\bar{\eta}}\right)+\bar{\eta}\left(\bar{\eta}+\kappa \lambda_{\bar{\eta}}\right)}{1+\eta^{2}+\bar{\eta}^{2}} \\
& \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{u, n_{1}}=\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{u, n_{1}}-\boldsymbol{x}_{u, n_{2}}\right)-\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{u, n_{1}}}+\kappa_{5, b} \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{u, n_{1}}^{(t-1)}
\end{aligned}
$$

The Lagrange multipliers $\alpha_{u}, c$ and $\bar{\alpha}_{u}$ corresponding to the optimization problems for $\lambda_{2, u}, \lambda_{3}, \lambda_{4, u}$ and $\lambda_{5, u}$ are introduced as follows

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \lambda_{2, u}=\max \left\{0,2 \bar{\alpha}_{u}+2 \kappa \lambda_{\bar{\alpha}_{u}}-2\left|\bar{\gamma}_{u}\right|^{2}\right\}, \lambda_{3}=\max \left\{0, \frac{2}{\sigma_{u}^{2}} ; \frac{P_{u} c}{\sigma_{u}^{2}}+\right. \\
& \left.\left.\kappa \lambda_{c}-c\right)\right\}, \lambda_{4, u}=\max \left\{0,2\left(\hat{e}[u] S_{u}^{2}+\kappa \lambda_{\bar{\alpha}_{u}}-\bar{\alpha}_{u} c\right)\right\} \\
& \lambda_{5, u}=\max \left\{0,\left(\left\|\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{u, n_{1}}^{(t-1)}\right\|_{2}-v-2\left(\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{u, n_{1}}^{(t-1)}\right)^{T}\left(\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{u, n_{1}}-\boldsymbol{x}_{u, n_{2}}\right)\right.\right. \\
& \left.\left.\left.-\boldsymbol{\lambda}_{\tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{u, n_{1}}}\right)\right) /\left(2 \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{u, n_{1}}^{(t-1)}\right)^{T} \tilde{\boldsymbol{x}}_{u, n_{1}}^{(t-1)}\right\}
\end{aligned}
$$

The subproblem with respect to $\tilde{\boldsymbol{q}}$ can be written as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \min _{\tilde{\boldsymbol{q}}} \mid \boldsymbol{q}-\tilde{\boldsymbol{q}}+\kappa \boldsymbol{\lambda}_{\tilde{\boldsymbol{q}}} \|^{2} \\
& \text { s.t. }\|\tilde{\boldsymbol{q}}\|^{2}=1
\end{aligned}
$$

The subproblem (19) can be solved with the aid of projection [16], with the solution given by $\tilde{\boldsymbol{q}}=\left(\boldsymbol{q}+\kappa \boldsymbol{\lambda}_{\tilde{\boldsymbol{q}}}\right) /\left\|\boldsymbol{q}+\kappa \boldsymbol{\lambda}_{\tilde{\boldsymbol{q}}}\right\|$. The subproblem for $\boldsymbol{b}_{u}$ is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \min _{\boldsymbol{b}_{u}} \left\|\boldsymbol{a}\left(\boldsymbol{x}_{u}\right)-\boldsymbol{b}_{u}+\kappa \boldsymbol{\lambda}_{\boldsymbol{b}_{u}}\right\|^{2}+\left\|\gamma_{u}-\boldsymbol{q}^{H} \boldsymbol{b}_{u} \beta_{u}+\kappa \lambda_{\gamma_{u}}\right\|^{2} \\
& \text { s.t. }\left|\boldsymbol{b}_{u}(t)\right|=1
\end{aligned}
$$

Due to the separability of the unit modulus constraints, the one-iteration BCD-type algorithm described in the Appendix of [15] can be effectively utilized to solve the problem (20).

## E. 3-rd round of optimization

For the subproblem over $\bar{\eta}$ and $\tilde{c}$, we continue to adopt the Lagrange multiplier method, and they are given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\bar{\eta} & =\frac{\tilde{\eta} \tilde{c}-\eta \tilde{\eta}+\kappa\left(\tilde{\eta} \lambda_{\tilde{c}}+\lambda_{\tilde{\eta}}\right)}{1+\tilde{\eta}^{2}} \\
\text { and } \tilde{c} & =\frac{c+\kappa \lambda_{\tilde{c}}-\tilde{\alpha}_{u} \tilde{\alpha}_{u}-\kappa \lambda_{\tilde{\alpha}_{u}}+\bar{\eta} \tilde{\eta}-\kappa \lambda_{\tilde{\eta}}}{1-\tilde{\alpha}_{u}^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$
